body:
@zuliani99   re: reporting on accuracy.

I suggest you look at Ludwig visualizations.  This [link](https://ludwig-ai.github.io/ludwig-docs/user_guide/#compare_performance) shows the example of the `compare_performance` report.  This [link](https://ludwig-ai.github.io/ludwig-docs/api/visualization/#compare_performance) describes the Ludwig api to generate that report from a Python program.  This [link](https://github.com/ludwig-ai/ludwig/blob/master/examples/mnist/visualize_model_test_results.ipynb) is an example Jupyter notebook illustrating how to call the Ludwig visualization apis.

If the standard Ludwig visualizations are not sufficient for your purposes, it is possible, as you suggest, to read the train/test *.json files to extract out metrics.  Here is [an example](https://github.com/ludwig-ai/ludwig/blob/master/examples/titanic/model_training_results.ipynb) of extracting metrics from the *.json files and using `seaborn`/`matplotlib` to display the results.
